The problem is that the cell that you just edited is still in &quot;edit mode&quot; when you click on the _Save_ button. Refer to this bug: [JDK-6349059][1]

The bug states that the problem was solved by setting a [custom property][2]. I assumed that the property is set when a `JTable` is created but according to my check, it is not. Hence I could reproduce your problem. Explicitly setting the property solves the problem. I suggest that you add the following line to method `initializeComponent` (of class `JTableDemo2`):
```java
jtable.putClientProperty(&quot;terminateEditOnFocusLost&quot;, Boolean.TRUE);
```
Also note that the default [layout][3] for [the content pane of] `JFrame` is [BorderLayout][4] so I suggest adding the `JTable` to a `JScrollPane` and setting the `JScrollPane` as the &quot;center&quot; component. Consider the following code (which includes all the changes I suggested, above):
```java
import java.awt.BorderLayout;
import java.awt.event.ActionEvent;
import java.awt.event.ActionListener;
import java.awt.event.WindowAdapter;
import java.awt.event.WindowEvent;

import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

import javax.swing.JButton;
import javax.swing.JFrame;
import javax.swing.JPanel;
import javax.swing.JScrollPane;
import javax.swing.JTable;

public class JTableDemo2 extends JFrame implements ActionListener {

    private JButton addBtn;
    private JButton resetBtn;
    private JTable jtable;
    private StudentModel studentModel;

    private JTableDemo2() {
        setBounds(300, 200, 550, 400);
        addWindowListener(new WindowAdapter() {
            public void windowClosing(WindowEvent we) {
                dispose();
            }
        });
        initializeComponent();
    }

    void initializeComponent() {
        JPanel panel = new JPanel();
        studentModel = new StudentModel(getDummyData());
        addBtn = new JButton(&quot;Save&quot;);
        addBtn.addActionListener(this);
        resetBtn = new JButton(&quot;Close&quot;);
        resetBtn.addActionListener(this);
        jtable = new JTable(studentModel);
        add(new JScrollPane(jtable), BorderLayout.CENTER);
        panel.add(addBtn);
        panel.add(resetBtn);
        add(panel, BorderLayout.LINE_END);
        jtable.putClientProperty(&quot;terminateEditOnFocusLost&quot;, Boolean.TRUE);
    }

    /**
     * @param args the command line arguments
     */
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        JTableDemo2 object = new JTableDemo2();
        object.setVisible(true);
    }

    private Map&lt;String, String&gt; getDummyData() {
        Map&lt;String, String&gt; rowData = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();
        rowData.put(&quot;Age&quot;, &quot;&quot;);
        rowData.put(&quot;Name&quot;, &quot;&quot;);
        return rowData;
    }

    @Override
    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) {
        if (e.getSource() == addBtn) {
            System.out.println(&quot;studentModel.getAttributeMap() :&quot; + studentModel.getAttributeMap());
        }
    }
}
```
I also suggest that you refer to [How to Use Tables][5].


  [1]: https://bugs.openjdk.org/browse/JDK-6349059
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/uiswing/components/jcomponent.html#properties
  [3]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/uiswing/layout/index.html
  [4]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.desktop/java/awt/BorderLayout.html
  [5]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/uiswing/components/table.html

